<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#E6EBD7" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post82543"></a>
	
	<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#333399"><b>Wyte</b></font><br>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#333399">Skin like Steel</font><br>
	<p>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#333399">Registered: Oct 2003<br>
	Location: Livin' in Northern Alberta, CANADA!!<br>
	Posts: 481</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#E6EBD7" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#333399"> <b></b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#333399">Wingdings, meet EQ!!  LOL<br />
<br />
Anyway...   fonts, target indicator, con indicator...  those all sound good to me!  <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt=""><br />
<br />
How about a new heavily optimized graphics engine?  /hint hint<br />
<br />
Looking back, there's been a ton of changes over the years to make EQ an easier game to play.  It's good to see they're not about to stop now.  Selecting a single item from a stack of 20 comes to mind, Geeez that was aweful.  Even now'a-days, making Solestice Robes or Celestial Essenses gives me carpal tunnel.<br />
<br />
I'm very interested in what the target indicator would be.  Myth 3 had an interesting one:   A circle under the mob with a bar jetting up one side, indicating the amount of health the mob/character had.  It changed color too, green being full, red being almost dead.<br />
<br />
Other games (ie: Sacrifice, prolly more though) had twirling gems above selected targets.<br />
<br />
I guess the problem with EQ is that the engine allows multiple mobs to be at the same X, Y, Z coordinates.<br />
<br />
What would really be the shiznit is integrating the target, it's con, it's health, and it's state into one visual effect.<br />
<br />
For example:<br />
<ul><li>A semi-transparent gem above the head would indicate your target.<br />
<li>The gem would be 'filled' to the amount of health it has, maybe even with a color gradient representing empty to full.<br />
<li>The gem vertices (outline of the gem structure) would have the con color.<br />
<li>The semi-transparent color of the gem (the walls) would pulse if this particular target was mezzed.</ul><br />
<br />
Now <i>then</i> I would be seriously impressed.<br />
<br />
<br />
Wyte</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
